{
    "id": "electronics/arduino-blink",
    "title": "Blink an LED with Arduino",
    "description": "Learn to program a microcontroller by blinking an LED.",
    "image": "/assets/quests/basic_circuit.svg",
    "npc": "/assets/npc/orion.jpg",
    "start": "start",
    "dialogue": [
        {
            "id": "start",
            "text": "Hey there! Orion here. Ready to make this LED blink with a microcontroller? Set up on a dry, non-conductive surface and keep power disconnected until the wiring is double-checked.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "materials",
                    "text": "Absolutely! What do I need?"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "materials",
            "text": "Gather an Arduino Uno, a solderless breadboard, two male-to-male jumper wires, a 220 Ω resistor, a 5 mm LED, a USB Type-A to USB-B cable and a laptop with the Arduino IDE installed. If you haven't yet, follow the 'Install the Arduino IDE' process. Check the resistor's color bands (red-red-brown) and confirm the LED's longer leg is the anode. With the board unplugged, use jumper wires to connect the anode to pin 13 through the resistor and the cathode to GND.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "process",
                    "process": "arduino-ide-install",
                    "text": "Install the Arduino IDE"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "upload",
                    "text": "Got it all wired up. What's next?",
                    "requiresItems": [
                        {
                            "id": "72b4448e-27d9-4746-bd3a-967ff13f501b",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "d1105b87-8185-4a30-ba55-406384be169f",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "3cd82744-d2aa-414e-9f03-80024b624066",
                            "count": 2
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "48cf736e-184c-4bd1-b9b0-15b7e9721646",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "037e6065-68a7-4ad1-9b0b-7778ecfe0662",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "fb60696a-6c94-4e5e-9277-b62377ee6d73",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "b6fc1ed6-f399-4fdb-9f9d-3913f893f43d",
                            "count": 1
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "upload",
            "text": "Connect the board to the laptop with the USB cable, open the Arduino IDE and load File > Examples > 01.Basics > Blink. In Tools choose Board > Arduino Uno and Port > your device, then click Upload and wait for 'Done uploading'. The microcontroller resets and the LED blinks once per second. Avoid touching the board while it's powered.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "finish",
                    "text": "Upload complete and the LED is blinking!"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "finish",
            "text": "Look at that! You just programmed a microcontroller. Always unplug the USB cable before modifying the circuit. For a deeper walkthrough, see the 'Blink an LED with Arduino' process. Keep experimenting with different patterns and sensors—this skill will come in handy for bigger projects.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "process",
                    "process": "arduino-led-blink",
                    "text": "Open the detailed blink process"
                },
                {
                    "type": "finish",
                    "text": "Thanks Orion, that was awesome!"
                }
            ]
        }
    ],
